@NFTethics I think the issue lies with desperation. People need to take their time. Make sure contracts are safe before buying. Maybe to reconcile the two trusted parties could offer code audits and people would look for those if they can't read the code themselves.
@NFTethics Lot of bored/crazy people come after others for no reason online as well besides that they can. See: streamer swat incidents.

@NFTethics Valid reasons not to doxx yourself as well. People can and do target others online even if they do nothing wrong. As far as I can tell the people who run this account aren't doxxed and I don't think they should be. Bad actors could come for revenge when exposed by you.

@NFTethics Demanding doxxing is just a shortcut people ask for to avoid doing their own research. Plenty of doxxed people can and do walk away from projects and go make new ones without reputational damage. It's not a valid substitute.

@NFTethics Understand why people want this but I strongly disagree. Everyone has a right to privacy. If we try to enforce this web3 will go the same direction as web2. Easy to fake a 'real identity', and if we wanted to verify think about who we'd have to rely on. More reasons to follow.
@0xQuit Any legitimate reason a project would want to hide their contract? I can't think of one.

Shouldn't it be normal to let people see your contract prior to launch so they have time to make sure it's safe and there are no issues? Is there any reason a project wouldn't? I'd be wary of any project that didn't want people to see their contract.

@al_hemyariii I get it, I really do. I've long since given up on getting on white lists myself - I just don't have the time to grind it out and I don't want to turn my twitter into a bunch of giveaway retweets.

@al_hemyariii You can release a collection with art considered "bad" and still provide something of value - maybe there is some utility to go with the NFT. But you'd still show the art upfront in that case, I would think - or you risk losing the community you built because they'll feel lied to
@al_hemyariii That's my problem.

@al_hemyariii It's not so much about the quality so much as people being so desperate to get in first to a new project that they are willing to spread something before even seeing what is (supposedly) being offered.
Wishful thinking but I think we should hold new projects to a higher standard here. Interacting with these types of projects just means we will see more of them.

While I understand wanting to get in early and secure a whitelist/presale spot (and thus following/retweeting/whatever) I personally don't think it's worth it until they've shown art. I'd hate for someone to find out about a project that turns out to be a rug through me.
Surely if you planned to release NFTs worth buying, you'd show at least some of the art off ASAP.
I don't get the recent trend of projects that start promoting without any art. IMO it implies they have none.
